title: For Sale/Trade:  Rock Island Armory "tactical"
postcontent:
This Rock Island Armory pistol is actually better than their listed tactical version. It has rubber finger groove grips, but the real upgrades are in the stainless trigger, hammer, and extended Beavertail safety, as well as the beveled mag well. It comes with 4 mags - two are Chip McCormick power 10 mags (10 round capacity), one is an 8 round Colt Mag, and another is a 7 round Chip McCormick mag. This gun has the regular full size grip that takes 7 or 8 round mags, black dovetailed sights (no need to machine the slide to get better after market sights), and the shorter bull barrel (I think it's like 3.5 - 3.8 inches). It will also come with a very nice Galco black leather concealment holster that has not been used up to this point. I paid $70 for it. 

The gun fires quite well, hasn't seen more than a few hundred rounds. Flawless with ball ammo and Federal Hydrashok, my hollowpoint of choice in a .45. I'm looking to sell or trade, but no hunting rifles please. It's a good price for what you're getting, so I'm not liable to budge too far off of it. Reasonable offers considered, however.

title: For Sale:  SHEPHERD 6-18x40 V1A Dual Reticle System Rifle Scope (618-V1A) Retail 1,100.00
postcontent:
ATTN : THIS SCOPE ALREADY HAS THE RING MOUNTS INSTALLED AND HAS FRONT AND REAR BUTLER CREEK FLIP UPS AT NO EXTRA CHARGE.  

THIS SCOPE RETAILS FOR $1,100.00. ALTHOUGH I PURCHASED THIS SCOPE I NEVER USED IT. IT IS NIB.

The SHEPHERD 6-18x40 V1A Dual Reticle System Rifle Scope (618-V1A) has such magnificent features as one shot zeroing in, visual confirmation of windage and elevation, instant range finding and bullet drop compensation, instant visual verification of the original zero, and so on. You will always find the brightest light transmission and the sharpest resolution in optics with the Shepherd scope.

The model 618-V1A has 18" range-finding circles for deer and military silhouettes. Please note that circles can be adjusted up or down to accomodate faster or slower loads.

Drop figures in inches from 100 yds / zero to the center:

Why some scopes lose their zeros and some don't?
Rule #1 is: In order for a scope to lose its zero, something between the reticle and the target must move.
Rule #2 is: In order to see what moved you need two reticles, each one to track the other.


The old type German scopes put the cross hair in the front focal plane. They hardly ever lost their zeros because the only thing between the reticle and the cross hair was the objective lens. The drawback was that the reticle magnified when zoomed and blocked out long-range targets. Americans put the reticle in the rear focal plane where it would not magnify. The main drawback with this was that it put about three more lenses between the reticle and the target. The American system was then three times more likely to lose its zero. The American was more convenient but the German system was more reliable.

Shepherd Rifle Scope gives you the best of both worlds with the drawbacks of neither. Sheperd uses the front focal plane location for rangefinding and bullet drop compensating circles. This gives Shepperd Scope the German dependability and, when zoomed, the circles do not block the targets but instead frame them and give you instant target engagement on any power. Then put the cross hair in the rearfocal plane (where the Americans do) in order to get the benefits of a nonmagnifying reticle. This patented Dual Reticle System lets each reticle monitor the other and thus allows for: one shot zeroing in, "at a glance" verification of the original zero, and visual confirmation of windage and elevation adjustments before you shoot. The Shepherd is truly the most reliable of all and the only one to tell you if something is out of zero before you shoot.

title: For Sale:  9mm Pistol with 2 mags and factory box
postcontent:
Fired one box in this 9 mm, so it is like new condition, it is not a HI Power, but it looks like one, FEG P9R-HP, double action semi automatic pistol,  comes with the 2 factory 14 round magazines, excellent factory walnut grips, and the factory box, $400.00

Here is a little history on them,

The FEG P9R is the derivative of the earlier FEG P9 pistol. Both guns are made in Hungary by the FEGARMY Arms factory (formerly known as Fegyver es Gazkeszuelekgyara NV). The P9R uses the modified P9 frame and action, but the classic FN GP-35 Single Action trigger system is replaced with Smith & Wesson Double Action system. In Europe the FEG P9R was also known as the Mauser 90DA, as it was imported and distributed through the famous German Mauser organization.

The P9R is a short recoil operated, locked breech pistol. The barrel is operated using a Browning cam system, and is locked to slide by three locking lugs on the top of the barrel, which fit into mated recesses on the inside of the slide, just ahead of the ejection port. Frame and slide are made from carbon steel and have blued finish. The Double Action trigger system with external hammer has a slide-mounted safety lever, which also works as a de cocker when safety is engaged. The front sight is permanently fixed to the slide, while rear sight is dovetailed.

Folks, the vast majority of semi-automatic firearms do not use 'clips', they use 'magazines'. Yes, there is a difference. Please try to sound as if you are at least slightly educated when you are buying or selling a firearm. I for one would not do business with someone who can't even use proper terminology when discussing the products they are buying or selling, and I would urge others to do the same. We have a hard enough time defending our right to keep and bear arms without having to contend with being accused of complete ignorance as well.

Thanks

title: For Sale:  Savage Palma Model 12 w/ Knight Force NXS 12-42X56mm + extras
postcontent:
***Price is $3,500***

I bought a Savage Palma Model 12 chambered in .308 as soon as they came out a few years ago, but I haven't shot it much and am ready to get rid of it. For exact specs on the gun, visit http://www.savagearms.com/firearms/model/12+PALMA (this is not my gun nor is it my picture or website, but it is 100% accurate to the specs on my gun). I have probably put 50-75 rounds through it. For the first 20 shots, I cleaned it after each shot to ensure its accuracy. I can personally say that it groups really well out to 600 yards, and I know very little about long range shooting, so it should do very well in the hands of someone who knows what they are doing. It has stayed in a Pelican Storm 3200 case except when at the range, so I will give its condition at 99%+. It has a Knight Force NXS 12-42X56mm scope with the titanium mounts from Knight Force. I still have the original box and parts for the scope, and the scope bikini is always on it to protect the lens. The stock and trigger are completely adjustable for fit and pull weight down to approximately 6oz. The butt is adjustable in every way one can imagine to ensure that it fits its owner properly. The rifle came with an Anschutz rail, so I bought the Harris HBR bipod for it and the adapter to make it fit this rail.

In all, the gun, scope, and bipod are all in very excellent/perfect like-new condition, I just don't need it anymore. It is extremely accurate at long distances (600 yards is as far as I've shot it, and it could group there even in the hands of a novice). I am looking to buy a custom stock out of Germany for my Perazzi MX8, so I need to sell this gun soon. You are welcome to come by and see it if you are in the area.

This sale includes the rifle, the scope, the scope mounts, the bipod, the bipod adapter, and any ammo I still have for the gun (should be anywhere between 20 rounds and 40 rounds). If you can come by to purchase it in person, I also have some miscellaneous reloading supplies that I will give away for free with this purchase including a brass case tumbler (possibly Frankford Arsenal). I estimate the reloading stuff to be worth around $100, and I have never reloaded, so they are all brand new. Any leftover used brass for .308 (~50 rounds) and 30-06 (~200 rounds) is also up for grabs with purchase of the gun.

The 3rd picture is below is exactly as my gun is set up but it has a different bipod. Mine is a Harris HBR bipod.
